                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94111/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-16T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 16, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>152. Please telegraph me as soon as possible your estimate of the probable
                    reaction in China should the President decide to invoke the so-called Neutrality
                    Act of May 1, 1937.<note n="17" xml:id="d473fn17">50 Stat. 121.</note> Any
                    further comments that you may feel moved to offer on the question of the
                    advisability of the President taking such action would be welcomed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
